The Ukrainian Parliament rejected, in the context of an amendment to the Criminal Law, the proposal to annul the paragraph on the indictment of the opposition leader Julia Tymosenko.
MEPs rejected the draft amendment to reduce the penalties for economic offences, which could have opened the door to freedom for the former Prime Minister currently imprisoned.
Tymosenko was sentenced in October to seven years in prison for concluding a disadvantageous deal with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not final and the court is due to rule on the defendant's appeal in December.
Tymosenko called the verdict a political revenge of the regime and provoked a process of suspicion of court bias also in the West.
The draft to repeal paragraph 365 of the criminal law, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was signed by 147 Members.
It would have taken 226 votes to approve it.
