The diet of an obese child: not eating breakfast and eating snacks for dinner
Over one third of children aged 9 to 13 are overweight, 9% of schoolchildren are overweight and 5% are obese.
As current research shows, obese children come from families with an unhealthy lifestyle.
This again shows the importance of the environment and the patterns that surround human life.
For example, on the tables of obese children, snacks are found 50% more often than in families with children of normal weight.
19% of obese people had fries at dinner according to the survey conducted with an awareness campaign "Obesity is not a coincidence"
In families of young adults, sports are also not a habit, as is now the case with most schoolchildren today - only 15% responded that at least once a week parents found time for active movement.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted during the last school year and involved 900 pupils from primary schools in the Czech Republic.
This was the second edition of "Obesity is not a coincidence", a campaign supported by General Health Insurance and Unilever.
Since the beginning, more than 12,000 students from sixth to third grade have signed up for this project.
One of the key factors that causes a dramatic increase in the number of overweight or obese children is the lack of adequate nutrition and not enough exercise.
"Only half of the children surveyed say, for example, that they eat five times a day breakfast - lunch - snack - dinner, which is a basic principle of good nutrition", says one of the results of the survey.
No breakfast and no snacks at dinner
Experts point out that for healthy development, some basic details are needed, such as a family breakfast at the same time.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of school families eat at the same time.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast alone.
And the worst thing that was found was that one tenth of the population doesn't eat breakfast at all.
Breakfast, however, is the basis of a good daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that in families with obese children, unhealthy fries are more commonly consumed.
Almost every student - not to mention the weight - drinks sugary drinks every day (70%).
More than 40% of the children surveyed do sport regularly but for parents, that's half, only 15%.
You cook your own food .
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own meals using options offered according to their own taste and personal opinion.
"The preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 years are far from ideal in terms of healthy eating".
Their favorite dishes include lots of cakes, meats, and sweets.
"The most alarming factor is the high preference for sweet lemonades", the survey results indicate.
For lunch, the pasta took the first place right before the white meat.
The children did not want any starches at all and the preference for fish and vegetable meals was very low.
Health
The survey also showed that children are ready to change their habits from the moment they receive ad hoc information.
"A review of a group of survey participants who completed the questionnaire following the 'Obesity is not a coincidence' awareness-raising session showed a strong determination to move towards a healthy diet", the survey results indicate.
The most striking example was the sugary lemonade, as children began to prefer drinking water.
Children most often checked the white meat and fish as the main course on the questionnaire and would reduce the sugary dishes and the "knedliky" (Czech specialty of bread flour balls or potatoes).
