The need for speed in Le Run is being debated across America.
The Commission
Originally a smooth race turns into a series of stupid mistakes made by people who have nothing to do with a routine morning trip to work.
It fulfills everyone's ambition to some extent, but it's useless if no one wants to do more.
The new installment, subtitled The Run, generated high expectations before its release.
He promised to take a new direction with the already old Need for Speed racing series and to come up with a kind of game from playable parts that would not just count on points.
So we were curious how the extra passages would be where the main hero gets out of his car and does whatever he wants.
As is already the case in the NFS series, the result is quite different from what was expected.
These are potentially arcade racing games but the whole thing is down because of some unnecessary mistakes that have been around for years.
These are not really mistakes but rather the expression of incomprehensible laziness on the part of the developers.
The adventure starts off very well.
You're caught up in the adventure of a hero named Jack who has character problems and to solve them starts racing illegally across America.
You're sitting behind the wheel on the west coast in San Francisco and your mission is to be the first to get to New York.
The idea has interesting elements.
The route is divided into ten stages and then into more than 50 races.
As a result, each race is run on a different route and the stages are planned in different environments that are quite distinct from each other and are interesting.
The player doesn't feel for a moment that the game offers him something identical.
Some environments are quite beautiful, although the graphic technical level is the same as the previous series.
It's not the end of the world.
But driving through the desert, in autumn landscapes, or in high-snow mountains is a very pleasant sight.
The trials are also sometimes accompanied by an atypical element.
For example, you find yourself in a sandstorm in the desert that makes you less visible.
Then in the mountains you have to be careful not to get hit by an avalanche.
Besides, the various races are well arranged one after the other.
There are only a few of them, but that's enough.
There are moments when you try to outrun the required number of opponents (as in a classic race) and then you run against the clock (classic time-clock duel) and then you have another duel with an opponent ahead of you.
Sometimes you also have the police come in and try to make things difficult for you.
The new thing is the exit of the vehicle.
It's more of an interactive animation when most of the time Jack runs away from someone and you have to help him by pressing the right button at the right time.
It's not complicated.
What's surprising is that there are fewer moments like this than you'd expect (to be specific, there are only three).
The result is that this element is not likely to interfere and is, in the context described above, the element that makes the game enjoyable.
The pattern of behavior is in the tradition of previous games.
Which means that there is nothing extraordinary about it at the moment, but we can't say it's negative.
As for the realistic simulation, you'll have to go see somewhere else.
But while we can find better in the competition the driving model goes very well with the type of racing design.
So it's all right.
Problems start to appear after a while.
Unlike the driving pattern, the collision pattern is not yet developed.
We don't expect this game to be a complicated deformation and collision, but when you don't have any idea of how your car is behaving in a collision with any object, it's not completely good.
During tight overtaking you sometimes touch each other slightly but otherwise your car starts in crazy flares.
Or it'll be crushed to pieces.
Thanks to the restart system, that's not really a problem, but it really bothers you.
The restart is done so that when you break your face or you're out of the picture the game takes you back to the last point on the route.
But you only have five restarts.
Once you've used all five restarts you have to start the game again.
So it's more of a tool, in case something doesn't go right, than something you can really count on.
Sometimes restarting doesn't help and you have to find the solution by remembering the track piece in question.
The big catch with this game is that the same actions are in the same place.
For example, there are certain turns that you have to go through in a certain way or it doesn't go through.
Otherwise, you will encounter 'civil' vehicles in a given location, always in the same configuration as you arrived first, fifth, 5 seconds early or a minute late.
What makes you angry is the situations when you see the opponent easily pass between two cars coming in the opposite direction and when you arrive, you have to either stand aside and twist them or brake them.
It doesn't matter if you go in front of him because it's "calculated" in such a way that for a given situation it always comes right near your nose.
Opponents have other advantages.
During the whole game, you arrive at certain places again, without worrying about the weather, and you always have the same opponent ahead of you at the same place.
It's the most annoying thing at the end of the game when you're driving on a long bridge in the opposite direction.
The enemy must at all costs go ahead of you.
When it passes you, it hides the view of the other vehicles in the opposite direction and you collide a number of times.
You can understand the goal of this game is to do something captivating and adrenaline-filled, but it's clear you get bored quickly.
And that's a shame because through a simple driving pattern the game is interesting and places with so much action that you don't have time to keep track of everything that's going on.
And it doesn't matter if it's because of the concept of 50 unique routes, that the race order is such that there's no chance of getting bored or anything else.
The original idea was to change cars during races.
You have to be careful with the gas pumps on the routes because you can change cars there, but most of the time the one you have is enough.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are ideal for cities, large American cylinders for straight highways and super sports cars with exotic atolls on highly technical conduits such as on sloping roads in the mountains.
And the challenge mode, which is racing in particular places that you know of as adventure, goes really well with the main plot of the story.
Not only do you get medals, but you also get experience points that add to your profile that is common to challenges and adventure.
When you reach the highest driver level, different objects begin to unlock:
It connects online with the Autolog function which, among other things, compares your results with those of other players and provides you with other functions in the community.
One of the hardest things to understand is the situation at the last race of the adventure.
You get in your car into the subway tunnel (it looks) where you drive in the dark on the tracks (it looks).
Your speed indicator tells you between 150 and 200 km/h (a priori) and behind you comes a subway train that sends the car straight to the garbage dump.
At the time of writing we had a discussion for a few days about whether anyone really thought through the creation of this game or whether the authors really thought we were fools.
The technical part of the game is not unusual, but the visual part is generally pleasant and in some cases really great.
What's disturbing is that in more extreme situations, the imagery doesn't keep up, and in some cases tragically.
This is especially true in accidents with a large number of participants when fluid imaging is no longer useful.
The sound part is good and the track is up to you.
In order to please the largest number and especially the youngest audience a new soundtrack was created in the style of "I mix everything", but one can expect that no one will buy the game for the music.
So the general impression of Need for Speed: The Run is really confusing.
If the game didn't have these stupid mistakes we could safely say that this is the best NFS production in recent years.
But this game seems like it's not over.
The fun is really good, but prepare yourself for mistakes to strike you in the eye with the force of an airfield reflector.
The students of the Velvet Orchestra in concert with the choirs of Charles University
For the third time, the Festa Academica festival will be hosting festivities that link International Student Day with the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution with a musical part.
During the festival, 20 choirs from the secondary and secondary schools perform.
The festival's pinnacle consists of two concerts organized on 17 November.
"Charles University has a big part in this festival".
"The choir of the Faculty of Education and Humanities is among the choirs, and the festival committee is chaired by the rector Vaclav Hampl", says the head of the organizing team, Jakub Calou.
The highlight of the festival is the high school and secondary school choir concert, which will be held with free admission on 17 November from 2pm on the space in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
The programme features the composition of the well-known Czech jazzman Karel Ruzicka, Celebration Jazz Mass.
The evening is marked by the "Students of Velvet" concert in the grounds of the National House in Vinohrady, where the choirs of the upper schools and Charles University perform.
The aim of Festa Academica is not only to celebrate International Students' Day with dignity and commemorate the 22nd anniversary of the Velvet Revolution, but also to present the public with the highest level of choral music and develop creative cooperation among young people.
The main organiser is the Czech Choir Union in cooperation with Jan Kepler High School.
The whole action is being put under the aegis of Bohuslav Svoboda, Mayor of Prague and Vaclav Hampl, Rector of Charles University.
The festival takes place from 16 to 20 November in Prague and Pardubice.
The programme also offers high-level concerts, musical meetings, student events and other activities.
All information will be found on the festival website www.festaacademica.cz.
