How Travel Prices Have Changed Since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at the time offered travel to the countries of the Socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists were on holiday to East Germany, the Soviet Union (Sotchi, Crimea and the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A major exception was the period from 1962 to 1972 when travel to Yugoslavia was allowed and then the regime began to take a westward turn and travel to Yugoslavia was very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for citizens of the socialist bloc (and also Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even within the framework of socialist countries.
In the event that the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually, for example to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter or else the individual travel was not allowed.
Travel agencies at the time also offered travel to the West, but you had to stand in line all night with a sleeping bag or have a "good acquaintance" within the travel agency.
And even after that, it still wasn't won.
The agreement for currencies that was a condition for traveling to the west was denied to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
However, the Czechoslovak currency was not exchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the agreement of currency (Western currency) for travel to the west.
The Czechs spent their holidays mostly in the country where there were many country houses and cottages that the Czechs bought themselves and this custom continues to this day.
The Czech travels have been a major revolution since 1989.
Although holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were at their peak until 1989, the Czechs spent 4 million holidays abroad in countries around the world last year.
The great paradox that we are not aware of today is that the most popular country is Croatia where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
The abolition of visas in the 1990s in neighbouring Western countries led to a huge wave of short-term visits, especially in Austria, Vienna and Germany.
For a long time, Czechoslovaks could not fly westward, which everyone wanted to see for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris travel agencies made Czechs sleep in tents in parks because our income did not allow us to pay for the hotel or boarding house.
The typical feature of a Czech trip back then was to bring your own canned food, sausage, etc... to save money.
Another important moment was the interchangeability of the Czech crown, which finally allowed our tourists, after decades of free Western currency purchasing.
Our standard of living and average wages increased, which led to another important moment around 1997.
As a result of increasing demand for travel, travel agencies have since 1997 started to prepare tours with air charter routes which, through contracts, have greatly reduced costs compared to what was available before.
In the late 1990s, the Czechs had visa-free connections with virtually all developed countries around the world except the US, which later made travel easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of tourism after the revolution, when the first charter flight to an exotic country, Thailand, was prepared from the Czech Republic.
Since this year, as every year, direct charter air travel has taken Czech tourists to the remote warm countries.
More than 100,000 Czechs visit these exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolutionary development happened in 2008.
On 17 November 2008 the EU removed Czech tourist visas and allowed our country to fully fit into the developed countries group.
In 2008 also for the first time in history Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time ever in history spent more than 15 000 crowns per person for holidays abroad including the additional charges.
