The Pavilion That Moved
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural history with highs, lows and happy ends: the Austrian pavilion for the 1958 Brussels World's Fair won awards, was a museum in Vienna, was empty and then fell into ruin.
It is now open again and is used as an exhibition hall.
If one is enthusiastic about postwar modern architecture, for its clear shapes, glass hangars, bright and bold looks, and new building materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the pavilion of the Austrian architect Karl Schwanzer for the 1958 Brussels World's Fair is a good and famous example.
The Schwanzer Pavilion was once awarded the "Grand Prix d'Architecture" for its lightweight, suspended steel and glass construction.
The construction is still considered an important step in modern architecture.
He made the architects so famous that he also built the Pavilion for the next Austrian World Exhibition.
With its legendary BMW four-cylinder house and adjacent bowl-shaped building in Munich, it finally became internationally famous in 1973.
Its pavilion design as a temporary building had been exhibited after the Universal Exhibition in the Swiss Garden at the southern Vienna railway station, was transformed, and in 1962 a 20th-century museum opened -
But the building was neither physically nor technically fit for a museum - no walls to hang the artwork, so not a good environment.
However, it was used for so long, until contemporary art received a new building in Vienna.
Since 2001, the building has been empty and has been falling into disrepair.
Now the Pavilion has been transformed by architect Adolf Krischanitz, it is now called "House of the 21st Century" and will be used as a museum for contemporary art in the future.
Tuesday night the Belvedere Museum opened, which owns the house, the first exhibition - a lucky shot in every way.
The new start was carried out by Agn√®s Husslein-Arco, who became the new director in 2007 of the Belvedere Gallery in Austria.
Husslein-Arco, promoted as an art historian to a considerable career in art as a young figure skater, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as the founding director of the Salzburg Museum of Modern Art, particularly successful in transforming politicians and protecting monuments, obtained public funds and private sponsorship and established the exploitation of these.
Except for contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba, whose foundation bears the same name, have been exhibited, a caf√© and a bookstore are located there, and an office is to be built there.
Strict supervision, small budget
Krischanitz was therefore the ideal interpreter for the production.
Not only because he had sensibly transformed and expanded the secession of Joseph Olbracht and won the competition, but because he had studied at the Technical University of Vienna and for him the pavilion was "an extremely important place" where he had seen "virtually every weekend" exhibitions.
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which lost in generosity and lightness following his move to Vienna and by its change of use.
The current transformations have presented major problems: the building was "an energy chasm", says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facades were changed, insulating glass reinforced with fiberglass was laid and the roof replaced with a special safety glass.
The beams of the thermal bridges were reinforced or replaced, and the asbestos-filled coatings were repaired.
Two basements have made room for the new farm, a lighting panel sewn between the house and the road provides lighting, a bridge leading to the entrance - it's almost a new building, but still the lightweight Schwanzer Pavilion.
The original exterior doors remain, the house is painted in a reddish-brown shade to protect against rust.
And the theater is even exactly the same as it was before.
And all this under close supervision of the competent authorities for monuments and with a small budget.
"Often good and cheap materials were found, and they are also pleasing to the monuments protection office", says Krischanitz and he draws attention to a raw ground in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and changes, the building remained flexible and light.
It would have been difficult with the Pavilion, "which came from Brussels", Krischanitz said recently, a typical story of "Drop-in-the-City".
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and yet it wants to "awaken a good conscience".
But in this case the 21st Century House is not in the wrong place, because if it is an urban construction accident, it is around the Swiss Garden that the newly planned "central station district" stands, with offices and apartments.
And another lucky break may come: the 21st Century House could benefit from the reinforcement of another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg bought the temporary Berlin art center, and as they say, she's already negotiating with the city to get a site in the vicinity of the Swiss Garden.
