Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
He wrote an extraordinary book here, which he accurately describes as "an anti-historical work".
It contains a few well-known names, important treaties or famous battles; there is hardly any ambassador or discussion of strategies or material.
He explains that it is not so much a book about what happened as a "book describing what it might have looked like".
"Beauty and Sorrow" summarizes the wartime experiences of 20 more or less ordinary men and women on both sides of the war, from young schoolchildren and botanists to climbers to doctors, ambulances and salesmen.
Some of them will become heroes.
Some of them will be prisoners of war, some of them will lose limbs, some of them will go insane or lose their lives.
Their lives here are like the candles of a church. When some of them go out, new ones are lit.
Peter Englund's book is a departure from traditional history books.
It denies the idea that the First World War was simply a terrible trench war on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Sorrow" skillfully describes other war theaters - the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, and East Africa.
The soldiers in this book are under hives; one spends Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; tsetse flies are an unmanageable problem.
This book is moving from the very first page.
War is invading these people's lives like a natural disaster, like a stinking cordite hurricane Katrina.
When gunshots ring in the distance, and you're a housewife, do you stay or do you run?
Who's coming anyway?
Almost no one can understand what happened, or even the reasons for the war.
According to Peter Englund, "the lack of facts has been overcome by speculation, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares, and rumors".
"Beauty and Sorrow" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor in the German High Seas Fleet.
Their stories are mainly based on memoir, letters and other documents already published.
Their versions of life can be terrifying or exciting, but they are most preserved by the accumulation of tiny moments and isolated details.
Most of them are about deprivation and the ability to get by.
In the story of a German school girl, Peter Englund writes: "Ersatz, everywhere ersatz".
"Replacement coffee, fake aluminum, imitation rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons".
He's continuing on the replacement food in Germany.
