"We realized that it was not that difficult to find them", says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report by DEMOS' think tank on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook is so full of personal information, says Jamie Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the site's advertising tool to find the people they're looking for with scientific accuracy - the way marketers have been doing it for years.
Jamie Bartlett's team found that half a million members were fans of far-right groups in Europe. They targeted them with ads, but instead of linking them to a new group or product, the ads invited users to respond to a survey.
By connecting with these people through Facebook, Jamie Bartlett and colleagues were able to interview 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - without leaving office.
"It's a new way of doing research", says Jamie Bartlett.
Some findings are not at all surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are more men, young people and anti-immigration.
But surprisingly, "those who associate online and offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic, and less violent than those who stay behind their computer screens".
The DEMOS study is just one example of how Facebook has become the new indispensable tool in the hands of scientists.
Think tanks, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study all topics that touch on health issues such as social trends, through "I Like", wall posts and statutory updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three content per day, the "data supernova" is generating an explosion in search, increasing the number of research papers whose name appears in the title of the site by almost 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the advantage of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you couldn't approach on the street.
"Before, when you tried to investigate people in the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them".
"You were supposed to go to the party, but they would never let you in", says Jamie Bartlett.
"Facebook avoids all this - you have direct access to their information".
Others say the site could offer a way to identify and treat health and social problems.
According to a recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison, and colleagues, young students who shared their achievements on Facebook while intoxicated were vastly more likely to be alcoholics than discreet students.
Megan Moreno suggests that fellow students, such as counselors, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student whose status would talk too often about alcohol.
"You can't treat a problem if you don't diagnose it", says Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Megan Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior, and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle, Washington Post.
"We know how to identify children at risk, and who would otherwise not be recognized".
Facebook also constantly accesses the information of its users.
The site's data team studied statistics on the love situation and Valentine's Day, the turnout rate in the 2010 midterm elections, and a national happiness index (thanks to only available information - digital freedom champions have long argued that the site could make its data treasure available to others for research purposes).
But Facebook users know that the site watches them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, the site is allowed to access your information.
