Seven lessons from Steve Jobs' lost interview, at the movies this week
After Steve Jobs died on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford - distinguished himself as a technical engineer and inventor of modern computing.
But what Apple fans can find most revealing in a recent interview with Steve Jobs that will be released this week as the first part of a film on major markets is how much this creative spirit had understood the processes and workflows of products.
He was undoubtedly a creator and a dreamer, identifying himself as a hippie but also being very meticulous and organized, as well as an organisational enhancer - a man who believed that many business leaders suffered from a "disease that made them think that a great idea makes 90% of the work... [but] a considerable amount of manual work separates a great idea from an exceptional product".
In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the television series "Triumph of the Nerds", which chronicles the birth of the computer, and he sat down for over an hour with Steve Jobs for a long, rare conversation.
By this time, it had been about 10 years since Steve Jobs had left Apple, and he was already working hard on his new computer company NeXT, aiming to popularise the Internet.
While a small portion of the interview with Cringely is used in Nerds, he says the main copies have disappeared in transportation.
It wasn't until after Steve Jobs died that a full video was found in the director's garage.
This slightly re-cut video is the basis for the 68-minute film Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which will be released in theaters next Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate in-depth interviews, Steve Jobs here seems surprisingly enthusiastic about exposing technology philosophies and his business strategies.
And incredibly attentive.
On four different points during the interview, the answers come long after the questions - between 10 and 15 seconds of reflection, during which Steve Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts, with the goal of providing a precise answer.
We also find moments when Steve Jobs' perfectionism resurfaces, where he seems eager to hear Cringely's questions, clapping his elbows to get him to speed up and move on to more important questions or topics.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, iPod or iPhone, there's a strange predictive aspect to Lost Interview where Steve Jobs evaluates what he sees as good or bad in other companies and shares his own vision for the future of computing.
It's one thing to read the posthumous evaluations of Steve Jobs' career, but there's something raw and inspiring about the man we see here, the anxious dreamer on the eve of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
He explains them and then applies them.
Here's a quick summary of seven remarkable episodes of Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
"All these years, I've always asked, 'Why do you do things?' and the answers are always the same, 'Oh, just because you have to do them.'"
Nobody knows why, nobody thinks deeply about things in a company.
That's what I found out.
Steve Jobs continues by giving details of his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
Confused about how costs were recorded - often starting with a "standard cost" assessed at a glance and then adjusted with a "variation" - he developed an automated factory that ensured accurate calculation of commercial costs.
On the opportunity to play a round at the Pope:
Steve Jobs tells the story of the "Blue Box" he created with Steve Wozniak - a device that was used to hack into phone networks and make free long-distance calls.
The device has been the subject of much writing in the past, but Steve Jobs' euphoria here in his description of the Blue Box as an act of appropriation is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box using a public phone, making a call and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while bypassing as many satellites as possible.
"We wrapped the ball around different things half a dozen times and you screamed on the public phone and it happened to you a minute later on the next public phone", Jobs laughs.
"We were young and thanks to this Blue Box, we learned that we could create something ourselves that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world".
We didn't know much, but we did invent a little thing that could control big things, and it was an incredible lesson, and I don't think Apple would have ever existed without it.
Steve Jobs continues by recounting a wonderful tour he and Wozniak developed: he called the Vatican with the Blue Box in the middle of the night pretending to be Henry Kissinger and asked to speak to the Pope.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two accomplices laughed madly just before the Pope himself was awakened.
About his love of technology (and Bill Hewlett's departure):
