How to Tell a Lie
A look at recent headlines shows how pervasive deception and lying are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women, each side accusing the other of lying.
Penn State administrators have been charged with perjury for allegedly covering up reports that a retired football coach sexually assaulted boys.
Last week French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught on an open microphone claiming to US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
The lie has destroyed careers and shaken countries.
New York congressman and Internet celebrity Anthony Weiner has been seen as an idiot by quickly making contradictory denials with irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign finance violations related to covering up an extramarital affair.
And then, no one who's ever lived through history will ever forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton started by lying during his second term about his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
The stories of cheating on school and college tests are legion.
There have been instances where teachers have given students test answers to show their performance ratings.
Mentors who should teach the opposite are sending the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How many deception are we facing?
In a given day, studies show that you can hear 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of them are pious liars.
Another study found that strangers lie to each other three times within the first 10 minutes of meeting each other.
Detecting or spotting lies is a vital skill that everyone must acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a social game like, say, charades, where the goal is to shout, "I got you", cheating detection is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades from prestigious universities that have conducted in-depth research on such projects, particularly in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the oldest myths about lying have been debunked.
Liars look you in the eye.
They don't always bark, red or move.
Do not conclude that liars are difficult to detect and difficult to expose.
A qualified lie detector can discover the truth by examining the structure of the statement, the micro-facial expressions, the formation of the question, and the response time.
I've spent several years examining scientific findings across the vast body and knowledge about cheating is still emerging, and it's clear that cheating detection is a modern skill that's easy to learn and useful for navigating our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, negotiating or managing.
Good liars are skilled at reading others, making them comfortable, managing their own emotions, and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more "self-centered" lies while women tell more "other-centered" lies - usually to protect someone's feelings - that married people lie to their partners less often than unmarried people (but the lies they tell tend to be huge).
We also know that if you are perceived as a disbeliever, others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How can you tell if someone's lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
This is called "establishing the benchmarks".
This helps to provide a reference point for measuring subsequent changes.
Look at the posture of your subject, the laughter, the quality of your voice.
You should be aware of anyone who is regularly shaking his feet so that you do not make unjust accusations when you see him shaking his feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for clues of verbal and nonverbal deceptive behavior.
Consider these clues as red flags, not evidence of deceit.
Deceptive people can hold their upper body when they try to remember their story, they can point their feet to the door, lean toward an exit, significantly change posture or present a "post-interview" relief - an exaggerated sigh of relief, a change of posture when all the difficult questions are over.
Interviewees often falsely state that the interview is over just to try to trigger the post-interview reaction.
So be careful of your subject vocabulary.
Famous Scott Peterson has slipped past the past while pretending that his murdered wife was alive, sparking a national search for her.
Deceptive individuals may also use distant language: "I have not had sex with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
A person may use a lot of "wood language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to be honest... if I remember well... to my knowledge".
This makes the response perceptual rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There's no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing the skills to recognize deceit is possible.
These skills will improve the chances of anyone avoiding being victimized by scammers in their professional and personal lives.
