The appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the Italian President on Wednesday to present the new government that will deal with a crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic disaster and put the entire Eurozone at risk.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he can form the government.
He is expected to introduce a cabinet composed of technocrat majorities, although it is unclear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said he would present the president with the results of his talks with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase", the former European Commissioner told journalists.
Monti did not say explicitly that he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles were overcome.
"The frame is now well mapped", he added.
Monti completed the process to form a government in less than three days, in less than normal time, as Italy struggles with a political and financial crisis that has pushed its debt costs to unsustainable levels.
The new administration, led by former European Commissioner Monti, must approve a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to restore the trust in Italy that had been affected.
The unstable market situation has put the yield of Italian BTP bonds above 7% over 10 years, the level at which Greece and Ireland have had to be saved.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of Italian employer Confindustria, told the media after her meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government very much".
We believe this Government is the last opportunity for Italy to get out of this emergency situation.
Monti's chances of success were greatly boosted by the support of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, which was forced to resign last Saturday by the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts will have a good outcome", said Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party.
The support of the PDL, Italy's largest party, is significant because until now many of its members had opposed the technocratic majority government that Monti is forming.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti government needs strong parliamentary support to implement what are likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockage or delay in its efforts could lead to another devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks added to the pressure by noting that Monti's bankruptcy would be a disaster.
Monti began consultations with political parties, trade unions and employers' groups and youth and women's organisations on Monday.
He'll finish his meeting tour Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who authorized an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief break at the end of last week, when it was clear that Berlusconi was going to resign, the costs of Italian debt have now returned to critical levels amid uncertainty about the success of the new prime minister.
To save Italy, with a public debt of 1.9 trillion euros, would be too much for the current financial defenses of the Eurozone.
Monti said his government should continue until the next elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement reforms before the elections are held.
Monti said he would like politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist that it should be trained only by specialists, an indication of their objections to a process forced by financial pressure.
