The asphalt of the UNAM would prevent the chassis
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at UNAM, develops asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture with better yields, regardless of environmental conditions and temperature
If the signals that the pavement was fixed, there would be no need to repair about 200 thousand cascades each rainy season in the Valle de M√©xico Metropolitan Area, warned Rafael Herrera N√°jera, a researcher at UNAM's Faculty of Chemistry (FQ), who assured that if the process of building and maintaining the oil pavement is adequate, the cascades could be reduced or even eliminated completely.
During his conference A Technological Opinion on Chassis, organized as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory he was responsible for is developing asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture with similar properties to asphalt, but with greater mechanical strength at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera N√°jera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some northern cities, to improve yields and, consequently, the formation of chassis.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called malthenes, which together give the stone its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behaviour of asphalt is that at high temperatures, almost 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees C it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform and changes during the day depending on environmental conditions and temperature, warns the chemical engineer.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Ciudad de M√©xico were mostly covered with flexible paving, made up of six layers of material, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and later compacted.
Each of the small stones that make up the layer, he reported, is bathed in asphalt.
When vehicles pass through it by generating effort, it allows the forces to spread very well through the pavement.
If the asphalt had been modified, it would have spread better, the chemical engineer said.
And they put on the asphalt a layer, which is called a rolling layer, of fine stone, that is, of sand that is also washed with asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide adhesion in the street.
As the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the effort, the rolling layer also requires that it be of adequate thickness and that the material from which it is made be treated.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also very important factors to consider, especially water, he says, as they have a significant impact on the yield of the asphalt layer.
When the soil gets wet, the water spreads inside the layer and it is difficult for it to come out, which softenes all the layers of the pavement and therefore causes the casings.
In the process of shaping a chassis, he says, the first thing that gets messed up is the rolling film and only later is the asphalt layer affected, but the damage does not take place immediately, but it is a process that must be treated at first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The National System of Researchers member explained that vehicle load is another important factor for chassis formation and therefore the thickness of each layer of pavement must always be linked to vehicle load and ensure its satisfaction, to avoid frequent chassis formation.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to be done to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow for easy repair of the chassis without the need for high temperatures.
