Moleskine, a trademark book.
Created about 15 years ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to restore the taste of writing.
He smells of adventure, hours of writing by the light of a candle.
The Moleskine book is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, its elastic, its broken white leaves, as aged by time.
Yet the Moleskine book as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a design but distinguished notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, is in charge of the launch of the new product.
The booklet is inspired by an ancient production technique, the mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton used to cover banquets, for example.
This type of notebook was very popular with writers and travelers.
"Moleskine brought back to life an old and forgotten object that was an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century", says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become Modo Modo's brand manager.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million obsolete pieces.
We are far from the secret production of the early years, when only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses Italian borders and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to draw a robot portrait of the buyer, because the notebook attracts both businessmen and students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and educated.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees at its inception, now has nearly 100 and has two offices in Milan and New York since 2008.
She distributes her notebooks in bookstores, from Fnac to small downtown shops, and she's managed to impose her identity.
"We have followed the pace of time and this new need for writing, despite the rise of e-mail", explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand launched an exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own book.
In August, she also launched a leopard cover at the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified its products: bags, calendar, pens, computer covers... the brand is based on a wide range of media.
A successful venture: In the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskine's history.
Why is the unemployment rate for disabled workers so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week of disability employment is now open.
Despite a voluntary public policy in place in 2005, the unemployment rate for disabled people is still twice as high as the average: 19%, compared with 9% for the entire population.
Discouraging ?
"No", says Eric Blanchet, managing director of Adapt, the organization that organizes the week for disabled workers".
"The progress made in the last 15 years is considerable".
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher".
"But there is still much work to be done".
It must be said that for disabled unemployed persons, the obstacles to employment remain numerous.
They are rather elderly: 37% are over 50 years old (average 17%).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have a bachelor's degree and out of the 2.3 million higher education students, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, longterm unemployment is very widespread: 53% for disabled people, compared with an average of 38%.
In short, these are criteria that make it particularly difficult to return to work, and that "constitute the core of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, general manager of Tremplin, an association established in 1992 to help companies recruit workers with disabilities.
Here's to the objective brakes.
The unspoken, changing mindsets, of course, but too slowly.
A study by IMS-Entrepreneur for the City in April found that managers surveyed had "a low level of knowledge about disability", with "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, with mental or intellectual disabilities".
As a result, private firms with more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, set by a law of... 1987.
The latest figures, dated 2008, show a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%", says Pierre Blanc, general manager of Agefiph, the organization responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
Evidence: the number of 'taxed' institutions and the amounts paid decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 tax increase law has put a lot of pressure on businesses", explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also means real awareness, especially in large groups".
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
